    <title>Combined summary - BIP16/17 replacement</title>
    <updated>2023-06-05T02:27:27.340604+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2012-February/001156.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In January and February of 2012, discussions were held among Bitcoin users and developers regarding proposed changes to the protocol. Specifically, Bitcoin Improvement Proposals (BIP) 16 and 17 were being debated, with some individuals questioning whether these proposals were backward-compatible enough to allow for continued use of old clients with each other.Gregory Maxwell argued against making breaking changes to the system, noting that any change would require a client update, which could not be taken lightly in a zero-trust system like Bitcoin. Other participants suggested changes to the version number and transaction structure, including replacing the "scriptPubKey" field with a new "hashOfClaimingScript" field and adding an "unsignedParameters" array. However, it was acknowledged that making breaking changes to the system would require everyone to upgrade their client.Despite disagreements and differing opinions, BIP16 was generally seen as the path forward that emerged from earlier discussions. While objections were raised by some individuals, there was no material schism in the community. Ultimately, the proposed changes were deemed backward-compatible enough to allow for continued use of old clients with each other, but upgrades would be necessary to make use of new functionality.During their conversation, Pieter Wuille and Dr. Andy Parkins discussed the difference between standard and non-standard transactions. Pieter noted that IsStandard() is used for accepting transactions into the memory pool, while non-standard transactions are verified just fine when they are in the blockchain. He also explained that if a breaking change were made to the protocol, such as adding a new transaction type, all users must upgrade to avoid seeing a fork of the chain from before the first new-style transaction. However, at the time of their discussion, both BIPs were backward compatible enough that people could continue to use old clients with each other.</summary>
